@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual --------------------------------------------------- Preface -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Internal" "Preface"
@{U}8.1) Preface@{UU}

   Laplace has been written  in C++. The source  code is primarily split  into
two separate parts: the @{I}kernel @{UI} on the one hand and some INTERFACE routines on
the other. The @{I}kernel @{UI} is the main part of Laplace - it contains the  routines
for mathematical calculations and all other capabilities of Laplace. The  @{I}ker-@{UI}
@{I}nel @{UI} is completely  independent of the underlying  operating system. It  makes
only use of the standard ANSI-C function library. All functions not  available
in the ANSI-C libraries (graphical user interface, multitasking etc.) are  as-
sembled in  the  @{I}interface  @{UI}  library that  provides  those  functions  in  an
OS-independent way.

   In some far days in the future I  will try to port Laplace to other  opera-
tion systems. To do this, only the @{I}interface @{UI} library has to be adapted to the
new OS (at least I hope). Currently  the graphical user interface is not  much
more than a C++ interface to Stefan  Stuntz' MAGIC USER INTERFACE, but I  hope
that it is not too difficult to implement those features of MUI myself that  I
use for Laplace (probably the layout routines, listviews... I don't use  those
weird gadget types, provided by MUI).



   I used the following tools to create Laplace:

 @{B}·@{UB} MUI V3.8 by Stefan Stuntz (see also @{"Readme.mui" LINK "Appendices.guide/README-MUI"}).
 @{B}·@{UB} GCC V2.7.2 by the Free Software Foundation.
 @{B}·@{UB} ENFORCER V37 by Michael Sinz.
 @{B}·@{UB} GOLDED V4 by Dietmar Eilert.
 @{B}·@{UB} TEXAS V0.1 by myself.


