@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ------------------------------------- Numerical integration -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Internal" "Numerical integration"
@{U}8.2) Numerical integration@{UU}

   If you apply the operation @{"nint()" LINK "Functions.guide/FKT-NINT"} to an integral, Laplace uses an adaptive,
non-recursive simpson-rule, to perform  the numerical integration. This  means
that the interval is  devided in several sub-intervals  and the value of  each
sub-internal is calculated by a linear approximation of the function.

   Laplace starts with the  given interval @{I}a...b @{UI}  and calculates the area  of
the trapezium using the formula @{I}I(a,b) = 1/2 * (f(b) + f(a)) / (b - a) @{UI}. Then
the interval is split at  the median @{I}c = 1/2  * (b + a) @{UI}  an the area of each
sub-interval @{I}I(a,c) @{UI}, @{I}I(c,b) @{UI} is calculated by  the same formula as above. If
the  difference  between  the  interval  @{I}I(a,b)  @{UI}  and  the  sum  of  the  two
sub-intervals @{I}I(a,c) + I(c,b) @{UI} is smaller than 10^(-n), where @{I}n @{UI} is the preci-
sion specified by the option @{B}$intprec@{UB}, the calculation is finished and the re-
sult is @{I}I(a,b) @{UI}. If the difference is larger, the same procedure is applied to
each sub-interval, which are split  into sub-intervals until the given  preci-
sion is reached.

   To avoid recursion, Laplace  puts the sub-intervals onto  a stack and  pro-
cesses on after the other, either putting two new intervals onto the stack  or
adding the calculated value to the final result, until the stack is empty.

   As you can see, the demanded precision @{B}$intprec@{UB} is @{I}not @{UI} the maximum differ-
ence between the final result and the real value of the integral, as you might
think. The error might be much bigger, because each sub-interval has a maximum
deviation  of  10^(-n)  and   Laplace  usually  have  to   create  a  lot   of
sub-intervals.


